and":"Paddington, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1410–04 Mar 1474":"1410–4 March 1474","1389–1456":"1389–1456","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1443–1491":"1443–1491","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1456":"1456","1389":"1389","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1474":"1474","ABT 1456":"about 1456","1509":"1509","1491":"1491","1429":"1429","04 Mar 1474":"4 March 1474","Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bold, Lancashire, England":"Bold, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Coddington, Lancashire, England":"Paddington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bold","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Staffordshire): from Middle English <i>bold</i> ‘dwelling-house’ (Old English <i>bold</i> the West Midland and northwestern form of Old English <i>bōthl</i>, <i>bōtl</i>), especially in the sense ‘castle or manor house’ for someone who lived or worked at the main house, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word, for example Bold (Lancashire), The Bold in Aston Botterell (Shropshire), Booden Farm in Haughton, Booth in Blithfield, and Bull Bridge in Penkridge (all Staffordshire). Compare   Bodle  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>bold</i>, Old English <i>b(e)ald</i> ‘bold, brave, noble’, which in Middle English developed the additional sense ‘arrogant, impudent, shameless’.","English: variant of   Bolt   and possibly a variant of   Bald   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Bollmann","meanings":["German:","elaborated derivative of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i> (see   Bold   4).","topographic name for a man who lived on a rounded hill, from Middle Low German <i>bol</i> ‘rounded hill’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, or a habitational name for someone from any of several places called Boll (see   Boll  ). Compare   Bolman  ."]},{"name":"Bowlds","meanings":["English: possibly a variant of   Bold  ."]},{"name":"Boldman","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German <b>Boldemann</b>: from a compound of a variant of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i> (see   Bold   4) + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Bodle","meanings":["English: habitational name from Buddle Oak in Halse (Somerset), Buddle in Fordingbridge (Hampshire), Buddle in Niton (Isle of Wight), Budleigh in Moretonhampstead (Devon), or Budle in Bamburgh (Northumberland), all named from Middle English <i>bothel</i>, Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’, probably denoting a homestead of some considerable size. See also   Bold  .","English (West Midlands): variant of   Beadle  ."]},{"name":"Bolds","meanings":["English: variant of   Bold  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Boldt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hermann, Kurt, Bernhard, Dieter, Egon, Gerd, Gerhard, Gunter, Gunther, Heinz, Hilde.","German and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold’. See also German   Bold  , compare   Bolt  ."]},{"name":"Bolda","meanings":["Polish: from the German personal name <i>Bold</i> (see   Bold   4).","Hungarian: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Boldizsár</i>, Hungarian form of   Baltazar  ."]},{"name":"Bolt","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bolt</i> ‘bolt, bar’, also ‘bundle’ (Old English <i>bolt</i> ‘arrow’). One of the most common senses of this word was ‘the blunt-headed bolt of a crossbow’, so it could have been given to an archer or to a maker of iron bars or bolts. <i>Bolt</i> was also used metaphorically for a short, thickset, or tubby person and for someone who was physically <i>upright as a bolt</i>, i.e. ‘as straight as an arrow’.","English: variant of   Bold   1.","Dutch, North German, and Danish: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldo</i>, a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>bald</i> ‘bold’. See also German   Bold  , compare German and Danish   Boldt  ."]},{"name":"Bolton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places in northern England named Bolton (Lancashire, Northumberland, Westmorland, and Yorkshire) or from Boulton in Derbyshire and East Lothian in Scotland, from Old English <i>bothl</i> ‘dwelling, house’ (see   Bold   1) + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."]},{"name":"Bolding","meanings":["German: patronymic from   Bold   as a personal name.","Danish: habitational name from a place so named in Jutland.","English (Middlesex): variant of   Balding   1."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Bold was born in 1410, in Paddington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Esq. Hugh Massey of Coddington. She died on 4 March 1474, in Bold, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1410–04 Mar 1474":"1410–4. märts 1474","1389–1456":"1389–1456","1429–1509":"1429–1509","1443–1491":"1443–1491","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1456":"1456","1389":"1389","1410":"1410","1443":"1443","1474":"1474","ABT 1456":"umbes 1456","1509":"1509","1491":"1491","1429":"1429","04 Mar 1474":"4. märts 1474","Coddington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Coddington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bold, Lancashire, England":"Bold, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coddington, Lancashire, England":"Paddington, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Coddington, Cheshire, England":"Coddington, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"14